<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Pronotum convex, 1.3–1.4 times as wide as long and 1.3–1.4 times as wide as head, widest above middle, evenly narrowed anteriad towards the broadly rounded apical angles and strongly narrowed posteriad; posterior angles approximately rectangular; median portion with or without indistinct wide longitudinal impression, this impression (if present) usually markedly deeper in mediobasal third; lateral margins with fine crenulation; lateral portions with moderately small and deep pits in middle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Elytra slightly wider than long, gradually widened posteriad from middle, 1.7–1.9 times as long as pronotum, posterior angles broadly rounded, with hind margins truncate at suture; medioapical portion of each elytron usually with distinct wide impression. Wings fully developed.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Abdomen convex, narrower than elytra, with distinct large and transverse wing-folding patches (tomentose spots) in middle of tergite IV, and smaller, oval patches in middle of tergite V; apical margin of tergite VII with very narrow palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">
Male. Pronotum slightly narrower. Protarsomeres 1–4 weakly dilated. Apical margins of abdominal tergite VIII and sternite VIII slightly emarginated. Median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[890,958,1468,1495]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1944,1969]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,189,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[178,1410,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Phlaeopterus hromadkai: 1—habitus, 2—labrum (dorsal view), 3—left and right mandibles (dorsal view), 4—labium (dorsal view), 5—mentum (dorsal view), 6—left maxilla (dorsal view), 7—aedeagus (parameral view), 8—aedeagus (lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3609635" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3609635/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) moderately wide, gradually narrowed towards the narrowed apex; parameres wide, long, significantly exceeding apex of median lobe, with two long apical and three preapical setae; internal sac divided into two very long clusters of acute spines. Lateral aspect of aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[210,278,1576,1602]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–8" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1944,1969]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,189,1917]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[178,1410,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–8. Phlaeopterus hromadkai: 1—habitus, 2—labrum (dorsal view), 3—left and right mandibles (dorsal view), 4—labium (dorsal view), 5—mentum (dorsal view), 6—left maxilla (dorsal view), 7—aedeagus (parameral view), 8—aedeagus (lateral view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3609635" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3609635/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Female. Pronotum distinctly transverse. Protarsomeres 1–4 narrow. Apical margins of abdominal tergite VIII and sternite VIII straight.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,436,1683,1711]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Comparative notes.</emphasis>
Regarding the presence of crenulate lateral margins of the pronotum and the general shape of the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName authority="Shavrin" authorityName="Shavrin" authorityYear="2020" box="[410,654,1720,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hromadkai" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[410,557,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">P. hromadkai</emphasis>
Shavrin
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[665,721,1721,1747]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[665,721,1721,1747]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Shavrin &amp; Mullen" authorityYear="2015" box="[867,985,1720,1746]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czerskyi">
<emphasis box="[867,985,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">P. czerskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shavrin" authorityYear="2020" baseAuthorityName="Rougemont" baseAuthorityYear="2000" box="[1039,1237,1720,1747]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufimarginatus">
<emphasis box="[1039,1056,1721,1746]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1070,1237,1720,1746]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">rufimarginatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Shavrin &amp; Mullen" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="czerskyi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">P. czerskyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the coloration, a smaller pronotum with more regular lateral crenulation, markedly longer elytra, and the presence of fully developed wings. Regarding the general shape of the body and the lateral crenulation on the pronotum, as well as the presence of fully developed wings, 
<taxonomicName authority="Shavrin" authorityName="Shavrin" authorityYear="2020" box="[844,1095,1828,1855]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Phlaeopterus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hromadkai" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[844,861,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[876,996,1828,1854]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">hromadkai</emphasis>
Shavrin
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1108,1163,1829,1855]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1108,1163,1829,1855]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is most similar to other species recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[407,477,1864,1890]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">China</collectingCountry>
, from which it differs by the absence of distinct spots on the elytra, slightly narrower pronotum and elytra, and smaller and less deeper lateral pits on the pronotum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1426,1936,1963]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" box="[199,1426,1936,1963]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1937,1963]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named in honor of the Czech staphylinidologist Lubomír Hromádka (
<date box="[1281,1414,1936,1963]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" value="1931" valueMax="2016">1931–2016</date>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="400" pageId="4" pageNumber="399" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1036,2034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1971,1998]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Distribution.</emphasis>
The new species is at present known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[926,974,1973,1999]" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation box="[1079,1146,1972,1998]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="4.[151,250,929,954]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,904]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1435,181,904]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 9. Distributions of Phlaeopterus hromadkai (black circle), P. rufimarginatus (black squares), P. ruzickai (black diamond), and P. septemmaculatus (black triangles) in China." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3609637" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3609637/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) in the Dalijia Shan range in 
<collectingRegion box="[180,254,2008,2034]" country="China" name="Gansu" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">Gansu</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[266,337,2008,2034]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="399">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,152,251]" pageId="5" pageNumber="400">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,152,179]" pageId="5" pageNumber="400">Bionomics.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[388,436,153,179]" pageId="5" pageNumber="400">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected at an elevation of 
<quantity box="[937,1022,152,179]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.475" pageId="5" pageNumber="400" unit="m" value="3475.0">3475 m</quantity>
a.s.l.. They were taken from soaking wet moss on a seepage on an almost vertical wall (location: C8); six specimens were found under stones quite close to the water, or collected from wet moss near a small river in a pasture formation (location: C5).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
